pe of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Brewes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewere</i> ‘brewer’ (an agent derivative of Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). Compare   Brewster  .","English (of Norman origin): Anglicized form of French <b>Bruyère</b> (see   Bruyere  ), a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heath’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of Dutch   Brouwer  , German   Brauer   or   Breuer  , etc., all occupational names meaning ‘brewer’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewster","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewestere</i>, <i>browestere</i> ‘(female) brewer’ (from Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). <i>Brewer</i> is the usual term in southern England, while <i>Brewster</i> is mainly midland, northern, and Scottish.","History: The <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrim William Brewster (1567–1644) was the son of the bailiff of the manor of Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, home of one of the earliest Puritan congregations. He was a prominent leader in Plymouth Colony from the 1620s until his death."]},{"name":"Brower","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Brewer  .","Altered form of   Brauer   or   Brouwer  ."]}]},{"name":"Beatrice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and French form of   Beatrix  , which was quite popular in England during the Middle Ages, and strongly revived in the 19th century. It is most famous as the name of Dante's beloved, and is borne by the elder (  b. 1988 ) of the Duke of York's daughters."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Beatrice de Brewes had at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1356–1399":"1356–1399","1373–1382":"1373–1382","–Female":"Surnud","1373":"1373","1382":